Coursera: Linux Tools of the Trade – File Navigation and Inspection

Overview

This lab focuses on fundamental Linux file system operations, including navigating directories, inspecting file contents, and extracting information from text files using command-line tools. These skills are essential for system administration, cybersecurity analysis, and general Linux proficiency.

Objective

Develop core Linux command-line skills to:

* Identify the current working directory
* Navigate through directory structures
* List and inspect files and subdirectories
* View file contents
* Display partial file output (first 10 lines)

Key Commands

* pwd — Prints the current working directory.
* ls — Lists files and directories in the current location.
* cd — Changes the current directory.
* cat — Displays the full contents of a file.
* head — Displays the first 10 lines of a file by default.

Tasks Completed

1. Identify Current Working Directory

The current location in the filesystem was determined using:

pwd

This command is useful for understanding the current context when navigating complex directory structures.

2. List Directory Contents

Directory contents were displayed using:

ls

This allows identification of available files and subdirectories within the current location.

3. Navigate and Explore Directories

The cd command was used to move between directories and explore nested structures:

cd <directory_name>
ls

This process helps map the file system hierarchy and locate relevant files.

4. View Full File Contents

The full content of a file was displayed using:

cat <file_name>

This is a fundamental operation for reading text-based files in Linux environments.

5. View First 10 Lines of a File

To quickly inspect the beginning of a file, the head command was used:

head <file_name>

By default, head outputs the first 10 lines, making it useful for quick previews of large files.

Key Takeaways

* Understood how to determine the current working directory using pwd.
* Learned to navigate the Linux filesystem using cd.
* Practiced listing and exploring directory contents with ls.
* Gained experience reading full files using cat.
* Learned efficient file preview techniques using head.

Conclusion

This lab provided foundational experience in Linux file system navigation and file inspection. These skills form the basis of nearly all Linux-based workflows, including system administration, log analysis, and cybersecurity investigations.
